Q

Perform multiple linear regression modeling, using the driving heart rate as the response variable. The aim is to estimate what are the factors associated with elevation or reduction of heart rate during driving. For that, you will need to use all the behavioral, environmental, and trait/state psychometric data you explored in Milestone 1. You will also need to use key control indicators associated with the study design, such as weekends vs.weekdays. The use of so many predictor variables would necessitate collinearity checks and a rigorous variable selection procedure.

Data corealtion plot

HR_Raw Full model

full <- lmer(HR_Raw.mean ~ 1 + Weather.mean + JF.mean +Speed.mean +ATP.mean +
               Accel_Energy.mean + Rot_Energy.mean  + State_Anxiety.mean + 
               B5A.mean + B5E.mean + B5N.mean + B5O.mean + MD.mean+ PD.mean + 
               TD.mean + P.mean + E.mean + F.mean + Trip_Period+Day_Type +
               Trait_Anxiety.mean + B5C.mean + Gender + (1|P_ID), 
              data = Df_rlevel, REML=FALSE)
